Microstructure of TaTiZr in HIP'd condition SEM backscattered images show a relatively coarse grain structure of the matrix (Fig.  3a ), a domain structure inside the grains (Fig.  3b ) and fine, submicron-sized precipitates of secondary phases inside the domains/grains (Fig.  3b-d ) and at grain boundaries (Fig.  3d ). The average grain, domain and particle diameters are ~320 μm, 4 μm and 0.25 μm, respectively.

T = 1400 • C, at which the TaTiZr alloy was HIP'd, corresponds to a single-phase BCC range. Holding at this temperature for 3 h was sufficient to homogenize the TaTiZr alloy and achieve the even distribution of the constituent elements in different regions of the produced alloy sample. The average diameter of these cells/domains (~4 μm) is about 80 times smaller than the average diameter of the high-temperature BCC phase grains (~320 μm)

After hot isostatic pressing (HIP) at 1400 • C for 3 h followed by slow cooling at 15 • C/min to room temperature TaTiZr has a metastable structure quenched from ~800 to 1130 • C and consisted of coherent, disordered Ta-rich BCC1 submicron-sized particles inside the Zr-rich BCC2 matrix phase. omega-phase nanoprecipitates and twins are also present inside the matrix phase. In the HIP condition, TaTiZr has high yield stress, 1671 MPa and 1440 MPa, at 25 • C and 400 • C, respectively, but its fracture by localized shear occurs almost immediately after plastic yielding at these temperatures.
